segments.text: This is Debbie Parks interviewing Mr. C.A.
Bonnen for the History of College Station Project, March 25th, 1983, at Mr. Bonnen's house, Side 1.
I think you can.
I'd like to start with some background information.
Where were you born?
And were your parents from Illinois?
What did they do for a living?
So you lived on a farm?
What kind of jobs did you do around the farm?
doing chores and field work and so on.
I didn't have to be somewhat older than Mary Hampton to do field work.
After I finished high school, I was never on the farm anymore.
What kind of education did you receive?
And then I was out for a year.
And then I went to the University of Illinois.
I got two degrees there, a BS and an MS. And after that, I went to the University of California for a year.
Did you get your PhD?
No.
see it as 1933 and all these federal jobs developed and I represented the experiment
What were your degrees in?
One of my first degrees was BS.
And you worked on experiment stations that were...
They were federally funded, is that right?
But they were in association with different colleges?
Yeah.
So long ago.
30 years.
50 years.
50 years.
Well, what brought you to the College Station area?
What's that?
What brought you to the College Station area?
Yeah, oh, for the job.
And what job was that?
Was it a teaching position?
Oh, I see.
And then later on you taught at the college?
Well, almost from the start I taught one course and then that was my research.
When you came to the College Station area, what year was that?
Where did you live?
For two years out there in Bryan, you couldn't find a place out here.
There was a small scattering of houses south of the campus.
And two years later, we moved.
And they told us about the house they were living in.
And so we got out here south of the campus.
What was it?
We came to Bryan in 25, I think, 27 when we moved out here on campus.
Where did you live?
What street was it on?
Well, do you remember what subdivision it was in?
Was it in College Park?
College Park, yeah.
Do you remember any communities that had developed out here?
a number of houses in what we called College Park and West Park.
This section hadn't been developed yet.
We bought a lot here in about 1934 or 1935 and built this house in 1936.
What subdivision is this?
This is... Is this Oakwood?
Yeah.
Oakwood.
Do you remember any rural settlements out towards south of town?
Perhaps in... Yeah, no.
This is all country.
I don't know.
Were there any farmers on the farmland?
Do you remember any specific communities?
Do you remember any communities in this area?
Well, the, what we now call the North Gate, it was the first developed, such as it was.
And then south, to the south there was the Oakwood community.
And there was a development west of here.
I think it would be the
See, this is the Oakwood, West Park or whatever it is.
Around what used to be the lake, there's a stream that runs through there.
I don't know if you ever noticed it.
Yeah.
Well, that was the lake at one time.
And the child around him.
Oh, really?
And there was a diving board extended.
I don't know if you ever noticed that.
Embankment runs across there now, but there was a diving board off of that embankment.
And a small child went out on the diving board and fell into the lake and ground.
And there were several children with her.
You know how children are.
They don't know what to do.
They're grand circles around here.
There were people living just a short distance.
When you lived in the subdivisions before incorporation,
How did you pay for your utilities?
Did you pay?
I don't know.
There was a corporation, maybe about five or six men, that developed these houses south of campus.
was incorporated.
And these men ran the corporation and made all the decisions about it and so forth before they were born.
Before 1938, the town college station was incorporated.
Then you paid them for the utilities?
Okay.
What were the streets like at that point?
Well, just gravel roadways and all.
Okay.
Do you remember where the sewer plant was located?
I'd like to talk about incorporation.
Do you remember some of the factors that brought about the incorporation of College Station?
Well, that history is rather interesting because it shows how aggressive Bryan was.
That's when they moved right out almost to College Station and took in all that.
See, at one time, our school district
Went clear to the Y, if you know where that is, where the roads come together and divide.
Yes.
All that country here into the Y was in our school district.
which, of course, takes a little time.
They immediately moved down, took in all that territory between here and there.
And, of course, they weren't able to go anywhere else.
There wasn't any other place for us to go but Sound.
And, of course, they, what do you call it?
They creeped around.
It's an area that's been flooded once in a while.
It's east of here.
Oh, it's east of here.
Is it Carter Creek?
Carter Creek, yeah.
We have to go across that to, you know, where they developed that.
Where this big shopping center is out east here.
Oh, yes, Post Oak.
Post Oak, Bookwood, Post Oak Mall.
That's a recent development.
Yes, I can imagine.
So as far as incorporation was concerned, the people decided that they wanted a city?
Well, they knew if they didn't incorporate, Brian would eventually incorporate the whole thing and it wouldn't get any bigger.
the railroad station in the city of Bryan.
So they were afraid.
Yeah.
We had good reason to be afraid of that.
Bryan has fought the development around the campus here from the beginning.
You're talking to someone who has lived through all that and feels pretty strong about it.
Well, that's what I'd like to talk about.
People around here were afraid that Brian would.
Oh, yeah.
Brian was very aggressive.
And of course, while we were unincorporated by taking anything they wanted.
I imagine the college kept them incorporating
campus.
So we decided that the only thing we could do was to incorporate them.
They immediately incorporated all the development community.
And at that time, our school district went right to the Y, where the Y are.
why didn't people want to be annexed into Bryan?
Well, there's a lot of history back to that.
You just got to... Of course, in the beginning, there was nothing but a railroad station here and the campus.
And...
The city of Bryan kept growing closer all the time.
And the minute we decided to incorporate, and of course that takes a certain amount of time, they incorporated all the land north of campus.
I don't know what the position of the regents was at that time, but apparently they couldn't incorporate the campus.
So they came about as close as they could come with their incorporation.
Of course, the village, it took them longer to incorporate themselves than it would have been.
Brian just, all they have to do is, we're moving here.
This is open territory, you see.
Well, had the community developed some kind of feeling of a separate...
Oh, yes.
Yeah, very distinctly so.
And of course, if you're a part of Bryan, it took in all the Mexicans and Negroes and all that sort of thing, and this is pretty much it.
college community.
And so you wanted to be your own separate community.
Sure.
Who were the organizers of incorporation?
Do you remember?
Well, I can remember two of them.
Mr. Gabbard, my next door neighbor here, who is dead now, and George Wilcox, who
moved away from the community.
I think he moved to Dallas or someplace like that.
Not recently, but fairly so.
And then a fellow by the name of Benny was mayor and was killed shortly after that.
Those three are the only ones I recall.
I'm sure you can get the names of the rest of them.
Well, how did they go about encouraging incorporation?
Well, I didn't have anything to do with that.
Mr. Gabbard was interested in the city, or at least that's what we agreed on.
I went.
My activities were involved with the school.
I had six children and he felt like it.
I would have more interest in the school than he would have.
So we divided the
They had a business up between the school and the city.
I went to the school and he went to the city.
Were there meetings?
Did y'all have meetings to discuss?
Oh, yeah.
A lot of meetings.
I can't tell you much about them.
Where were they held?
Well, we had a school out here.
The meetings were either in a public building or in the home of one of the persons who were in the meetings.
It was all very primitive, you know.
Was it kind of word of mouth, or did they post signs that there would be a meeting?
I don't remember about that.
Do you remember the petition that was circulated to ask for an election?
No, I don't remember that.
How would you say the board of directors or the faculty on campus felt about being incorporated?
I wasn't aware of any protest or anything like that.
Were they in favor then?
They must have been.
You brought up the fact that Dr. Benny was one of the active members, and he became the first mayor.
Can you give me any information about him, why he was interested in developing the city?
Well, I just know that that group initiated the,
the activity that led to the incorporation.
I don't know anything about their position and so on.
They must have all been for it because they got together and arranged for the incorporation.
Do you know anything about the man?
Can you remember anything about him?
Benny?
Not much.
He was killed right after he was, shortly after he was elected mayor.
Right out the east gate.
Probably had his mind on something and drove out there.
What's that?
It was a car accident?
Yeah.
What happened with another car?
I presume so.
It was right there at the east gate and he must have driven out into the, see there wasn't much traffic here then and he probably had his mind on something.
And he was in an accident?
Well, apparently you were head of a committee after he was in the accident to try to find or to encourage somebody else to run for mayor.
No, I hadn't.
See, all my activities have been with the school.
Do you remember talking to Frank Anderson about running for mayor?
No, I don't think I had anything to do with that.
He's a good friend of mine.
I'm sure I voted for him and so on.
I didn't take much of an active part in the city itself or what they did or what they were going to do and that sort of thing.
I left that to my neighbor, Mr. Gerber.
Mr. Anderson was the second mayor, and could you tell me why people would want him for mayor?
What qualities he had?
He was an outstanding individual.
See, he came here.
head of the A&M track team shortly after he came and .
stood for than I do, but I had a son on the track team, and he was a very sincere, very fine individual.
In fact, they named the A&M track Anderson Track now.
That's right, I saw that.
And that was well justified.
I'd like to talk about the education, the public school system in College Station.
You were on the school board for several years.
Do you remember what years you served the school board?
Well, the school was
was on the campus until 1940, February 1940.
And Bill Sparks, I don't know whether you ever heard of him or not, but he was a real estate man and a very fine individual.
And he and I raised the money.
build the first school off the campus.
Off the campus?
I don't remember.
There were a lot of little country schools around and they were all consolidated with College Station School.
I don't remember anything about that.
It was done before I came on the school board.
See, I helped raise the money for the movement of the school, the campus, and then in 44 I was elected to the school board.
And how long did you serve?
until 1959, 44 to 59, 15 years.
Do you know of any of the other communities that were consolidated with College Station?
Well, all these little districts around us were.
There you go.
I think after they were consolidated, there wasn't anything but our school and Wellvern and then down in the end of the county.
And they were eventually taken into the Navasota School District.
What's the name of the little town down below?
Milliken.
Milliken.
Milliken.
That was all taken in.
They were closer to Navasota than they were to
Do you remember the school on campus?
Yeah, it was a, stuck, stuck a building in a part of what is now the
where the Aggies lived, the dormitory.
It was a stucco building.
I imagine there was five or six rooms in it.
And then there was an old dormitory on the campus.
I forget the name of it, but you can find out what it was.
Was it Pfeiffer?
Pfeiffer Hall, that's right.
Do you remember what they called a teacherage, a place where teachers lived?
No, I don't remember that.
I saw a reference to that and wondered about it.
I think that must have been before I came here.
Did professors teach in the school that was on campus?
In the public school?
No.
No.
Your children went to the school that was on campus, is that right?
Can you tell me a little bit about, you said that you helped raise the money to locate the school off campus.
Can you tell me a little bit about that?
All I remember about it was that Bill Sparks and I were appointed to the job of raising this money.
See we had no
This is College Station because it has the name The Depot.
That's where we got our name.
Did you not have any taxes?
Did you have taxes?
Not until we were incorporated.
So you and Mr. Sparks had to raise the money, is that right?
We had to double the valuations on practically all property to get the basis for the money that was used for the school.
But this is not before you got the school moved off campus, was it?
How is that again?
What I'm wondering is that the school was located on campus, and you and Mr. Sparks and other men were interested in getting it off campus.
Well, we were ordered off the campus.
The university ordered us off the campus.
Okay, and there was a school board, and how did they have money to run the school?
I mean, apparently you needed to raise the money to move the school off campus.
Could you tax the people at that time?
I don't remember about that.
Okay, so the school ordered you off.
In the spring semester of 1943.
So you and Mr. Sparks helped raise the money to locate the school.
Do you remember the people, were the people submitting money to buy land?
Is that what it was?
I'm sorry to be so slow.
You get to be 86 years old.
I did pretty well when I was 85, but since then I've been pretty slow at recalling things.
You know, it's heck to be old.
I can imagine.
But, you know, that's fine.
Quite all right.
As I can remember in my research, money was donated and the Hollick Lane track was bought.
You mean that's south of campus here?
Mm-hmm.
Well, a man by the name of Clark, F.D.
Clark, I think it was, who was
college prof, and also a real estate man.
And he developed all this out of the campus.
He was of that group that developed College Park and then on south.
That's about all I remember about it.
It was in the hands of people like that who had charges of development.
Remember, this was a comparatively unorganized community.
And there was five or six men that formed a corporation that
all the land west of this development here.
And then Burgess and Sparks and another fellow
whose name I don't recall, but who was killed shortly after they were organized.
He was killed in an automobile accident south of here.
And Sparks and Burgess were at a card party that night.
And they got word while they were at the card party that
And he was killed.
And Burgess said, George, I just bought him out this morning.
And that's the first sparks Neil got.
And the sparks cut loose from Burgess and went over here and developed across the highway.
College Hills Estate?
It wasn't Redmond.
Mr. Redmond built that.
Redmond Terrace.
All these things happen that are run by somebody else that I didn't have anything to do with.
It's hard to remember.
It's hard to recall.
See, Brian came out and incorporated
most of that land where they are now and cut us off there.
Brian seemed to have the, they were incorporated and had all the knowledge of these things.
take advantage of us whenever they wanted to.
You can probably understand why we feel so bad about them.
We wouldn't give them a meal unless we had to.
Let me stop right here.
